snippet.textDisplay: It is shocking and sad to see so much indecent criticism over Salman Ahmad and ridiculing him to such great lengths and while at the same time declaring Junoon is nothing without Ali Azmat. Do you guys forget that Salman is the guy who did all the compositions for almost all the songs Junoon's ever made, or the fact he formed the band or the fact he still continues to contribute worldwide as a respected musician? Criticism of the song and personal preference of having Ali Azmat over vocals is a separate matter and understandable since I myself would have liked to see him singing this. That being said however it is unjustified to degrade the whole performance still based on his absence. Due to personal differences between Salman, Azmat is no longer part of Junoon, but do you think that you are the only ones who think without Azmat the band is incomplete? Ofcourse the producers also know this and since getting Azmat onboard was not happening they chose the next best alternatives. Rahat and Ali Noor were decent choice in my opinion. 'Sayonee' is also a song which was 'safer' in comparison to other Junoon's work to cover than for example 'Jazba Junoon' or 'Garaj Baras' in which Azmat utilizes his energetic vocal range to good use. Yes Salman could have opted for a different song which was not part of pre-breakup era but I think the nostalgia factor and also the fact this song has not being covered in the recent past on a modern studio probably led to the decision of choosing this song. Speaking of the song itself, you can not compare it to original anyway since Salman merged the chorus and composition from another Junoon's song 'Saayein'  as well to give this cover another nostalgic twist and slightly longer playtime which also highlights Salman's sublime solo

snippet.textDisplay: What  did you do to the song coke "studio? I love rahat and respect noori but they clearly have no bit of the sort of energy required to sing "Sayoonee by ALI AZMAT" its Ali azmats song, only he has the energy to make one feel "sayonee" with giving all those goosebumps and rebel thoughts travelling through ones veins while listening to it. You may experiment with it and assign some new young singers to sing its cover but why put such great singers to a test that they would inevitably fail?? Why would you turn it into a soft melody and look at that monkey Aabu of Aladin, Salman, his *MashaAllah* at the end is a disguised proclamation of the failure of the song. I'm disappointed. snippet.textDisplay: I don't understand what all the hype is about. We know for certain that Junoon will not be getting back together due to the differences between Ali and Salman so that's the end of one argument. Now for Rahat, true that this rendition is a lot different to the original and for some this may be indifferent but we need to understand that this is a rendition. That's what coke studio is about, a rendition. So this is a different composition to the original. That being said there are many who will like this version over the original and vice versa. I, in particular don't like this but if you don't like it then just change the song, what's the point of all this obnoxious name calling and vulgarity. The essence of the song and it's composition is based on the singer/composers ideas and the listeners state of mind. In short, please avoid being illiterate fools and leave it be. As they say, Love it or leave it :). P.S: This post is not directed to anyone or any person but a general comment. Hopefully people will stop all the name calling and avoid using swear words towards each other. Thanks
